  :sha256           "231c8855745a4b97"
  :prose
"(chapter
  :n 03
  :title \"Hash Tables — the trick of the good address\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"The post office in a small town has a wall of small metal boxes,
   numbered 1 to 800. When a letter arrives for you, the postmaster
   looks at your name and does a small trick to decide which box.
   Something like: take the first three letters of your last name,
   turn them into numbers, add them, mod-800 the result. Now she
   drops the letter in that box. When you come to pick up your mail,
   you do the same trick and go straight to the box. No walking
   the whole wall. The address is the trick, not the walk.\"

  :what-it-is
  \"A hash table is a data structure that maps keys to values with (on
   average) constant-time lookup, insertion, and deletion. The
   fundamental trick is a hash function — a function that turns a key
   into a small integer, the 'address' inside the table. You use the
   address as the index into an array. Constant-time in, constant-
   time out.\"

  :why-it-exists
  \"Because O(1) lookup on a keyed collection is the difference between
   a program that runs and a program that hangs. Dictionaries in
   Python. Maps in Java. Objects in JavaScript. All the same shape.
   The trick — hash the key, use the hash as an index — is one of
   the most important ideas in practical computing.\"

  :how-it-works
  \"You have an underlying array of some size N. You have a hash
   function H that maps any key to an integer in the range [0, N). To
   insert (key, value): compute H(key), go to array[H(key)], store
   the pair. To look up: compute H(key), go to array[H(key)], read.

   Two keys can hash to the same address (a 'collision'). Two common
   solutions: chaining (each array slot holds a small linked list of
   items that hashed there; on lookup, walk the list looking for the
   matching key) and open addressing (on collision, try the next
   slot, wrapping around).

   When the array fills up too much, performance degrades. So the
   table resizes — allocates a bigger array, rehashes all the keys
   into it. This is O(N) once, but amortized O(1) per insertion over
   time.\"

  :where-in-the-world
  \"Almost everywhere. Python dict. JavaScript Object and Map. Java
   HashMap. Go map. Ruby Hash. C++ unordered_map. Every modern language
   has a hash-table map as the go-to for keyed collections.

   Database indexes often use hash tables (or tree structures — see
   next chapter). Load balancers hash request URLs to servers.
   Distributed caches like Memcached and Redis are hash tables at
   the core. Compilers use hash tables to look up symbols. Every text
   editor uses one to look up commands.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"; Hash table with chaining, using a vector of lists

   (define (make-hash-table size)
     (make-vector size '()))

   (define (hash-key key size)
     (modulo (equal-hash key) size))

   (define (ht-put! table key value)
     (let* ((size (vector-length table))
            (i (hash-key key size))
            (chain (vector-ref table i))
            (existing (assoc key chain)))
       (if existing
           (set-cdr! existing value)
           (vector-set! table i (cons (cons key value) chain)))))

   (define (ht-get table key)
     (let* ((size (vector-length table))
            (i (hash-key key size))
            (chain (vector-ref table i))
            (existing (assoc key chain)))
       (if existing (cdr existing) #f)))

   (define (ht-delete! table key)
     (let* ((size (vector-length table))
            (i (hash-key key size))
            (chain (vector-ref table i))
            (new-chain (filter (lambda (p) (not (equal? (car p) key))) chain)))
       (vector-set! table i new-chain)))

   ; usage
   (define h (make-hash-table 16))
   (ht-put! h 'alice 30)
   (ht-put! h 'bob 42)
   (ht-get h 'alice)   ; => 30
   (ht-get h 'carol)   ; => #f\"

  :on-hash-functions-briefly
  \"A good hash function distributes keys uniformly across the
   address range. For strings, a common approach is a polynomial
   hash: multiply an accumulator by a small prime (like 31) and add
   the next character's code. For integers, sometimes the key itself
   is a fine hash; sometimes it needs to be scrambled first (a
   'mix' function). Cryptographic hashes (SHA, BLAKE) are extreme
   overkill for hash tables — they are designed for adversarial
   settings, and they are slow. Use them for security, not for
   hash-map performance.\"

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Peirce's index is at the heart of hashing — the hash of a key is
   an index pointing to where the value lives. The hash is not the
   value; it is the mark that leads to it. Wittgenstein-late would
   note that a good hash function belongs to the community of use —
   it works because everyone (writer, reader, table) computes the
   same H on the same key. If two participants used different H
   functions, the whole system would collapse. Meaning by consensus.\"
)
")
